A pancreatic neuroendocrine neoplasm that has spread extensively to other anatomic sites or is no longer responding to treatment.

label.value: Unresectable Clear Cell Renal Cell Carcinoma

value.value: A clear cell renal cell carcinoma that is not amenable to surgical resection.

A device consisting of a tube containing flexible optic fibers that may be inserted into a body opening to allow a doctor to examine hollow organs inside the body. The result may be viewed on a video screen. It has diagnostic (e.g., biopsy) and therapeutic capabilities.
Pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma that is resistant to treatment.

Terminology developed by a collaboration between the Integrated Canine Data Commons (ICDC) and NCIt EVS to support research into the feasibility of pet dogs with spontaneous cancers as models of human disease to evaluate new drugs, immunotherapeutic agents and treatments for further development for human cancer patients.
Pancreatic carcinoma that has spread extensively to other anatomic sites or is no longer responding to treatment.
A neuroendocrine tumor that is not amenable to surgical resection.
A lung neuroendocrine neoplasm that is not amenable to surgical resection.
A digestive system neuroendocrine neoplasm that is not amenable to surgical resection.
A pancreatic neuroendocrine neoplasm that is not amenable to surgical resection.

An oncolytic viral agent containing the oncolytic, live-attenuated, replication-competent strain of the avian paramyxovirus Newcastle disease virus (NDV) that has been engineered to include a transgene encoding granulocyte-macrophage colony-stimulating factor (GM-CSF), with potential antineoplastic and immunostimulating activities. Upon administration, MEDI5395 specifically infects and replicates in cancer cells. This may result in a direct cytotoxic effect involving the lysis of tumor cells via apoptotic mechanisms and may eventually lead to an inhibition of cancer cell proliferation through the increased production and secretion of pro-inflammatory cytokines and chemokines which are able to recruit mediators of both the innate and adaptive immune responses. Additionally, the inclusion of the GM-CSF transgene in the viral construct leads to expression of GM-CSF, which may potentiate and strengthen the anti-tumor immune response.
An ovarian carcinoma that has spread extensively to other anatomic sites or is no longer responding to treatment.
A space on a paper form or an on-screen graphical display that can be filled or selected to choose an option.
A diagnostic or therapeutic procedure in which an endoscope is inserted in a tubular organ to examine the structural architecture and/or remove abnormal tissues.
A person or group that facilitates the exchange of items or information.
A response that indicates that the degree of erythematous color change is dusky pink.
A response that indicates that the degree of erythematous color change is dull red.
A response that indicates that the degree of erythematous color change is brilliant red.
A response that indicates that the degree of erythematous color change is deep red-purple.
A verrucous carcinoma that arises from the skin. It usually affects the palms, soles, and distal digits.

label.value: Skin Squamous Cell Carcinoma with Osteoclast-Like Giant Cells

value.value: A rare squamous cell carcinoma of the skin characterized by the presence of multinucleated non-neoplastic giant cells that resemble osteoclasts.
A rare, poorly differentiated squamous cell carcinoma of the skin. It is characterized by the presence of tumor cells islands surrounded and infiltrated by lymphocytes and plasma cells.

label.value: Skin Squamous Cell Carcinoma with Sarcomatoid Differentiation

value.value: A rare carcinoma of the skin characterized by the presence of squamous cell carcinomatous and sarcomatous components.

The presence of multiple serrated polyps in the colon and/or rectum. The polyps are predominantly sessile serrated adenomas/polyps.  A minority of the polyps are microvesicular variants of hyperplastic polyps.
Any subcellular or molecular event, process, or condition concerned with storing and generating metabolic energy.

A group of hereditary neoplastic syndromes that affect the colon and rectum. Included in this grouping are hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer (HNPCCC) , familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP), and the hamartomatous polyposis syndromes.

label.value: Locally Advanced Oral Cavity Squamous Cell Carcinoma

value.value: Oral cavity squamous cell carcinoma that has spread from its original site of growth to nearby tissues or lymph nodes.

label.value: Locally Advanced Laryngeal Squamous Cell Carcinoma

value.value: Laryngeal squamous cell carcinoma that has spread from its original site of growth to nearby tissues or lymph nodes.

label.value: Locally Advanced Squamous Cell Carcinoma of Unknown Primary

value.value: A squamous cell carcinoma of unknown primary that has spread from its original site of growth to nearby tissues or lymph nodes.
A hyperkeratotic skin lesion that occurs in patients who have been exposed to arsenic.
A finding indicating that an individual has been exposed to arsenic.
A hyperkeratotic skin lesion that occurs in patients with a history of prolonged exposure to psoralen and ultraviolet A (PUVA) therapy.

label.value: Psoralen and Ultraviolet A (PUVA) Therapy Exposure

value.value: A finding indicating that a patient has been exposed to psoralen and ultraviolet A (PUVA) therapy for a benign or malignant condition.

A small molecule inhibitor of class I phosphatidylinositol 3 kinase (PI3K), with potential antineoplastic activity. Upon administration, pictilisib selectively binds to PI3K in an ATP-competitive manner, inhibiting the production of the secondary messenger phosphatidylinositol-3,4,5-trisphosphate (PIP3) and activation of the PI3K/Akt signaling pathway. This may result in inhibition of tumor cell growth, motility and survival in susceptible tumor cell populations. Activation of the PI3K/Akt signaling pathway is frequently associated with tumorigenesis; dysregulated PI3K/Akt signaling may contribute to tumor resistance to a variety of antineoplastic agents.
The discipline concerned with the application of scientific knowledge to solve practical issues in commerce or industry.
A scientist who studies or works in genetics.
A health professional who has a graduate degree or specialized training in the areas of genetics and genetic counseling.
A student who is enrolled in courses and studying to be a genetic counselor.
Positron emission tomography that uses a tracer other than fluoro-2-deoxy-D-glucose (FDG).

Cardiomyopathy resulting from the deposition of misfolded transthyretin. The condition can be classified by the presence (hereditary transthyretin amyloid) or absence (wild-type transthyretin amyloid) of mutation(s) in the TTR gene, encoding transthyretin.
A benign intraepidermal squamoproliferative neoplasm characterized by irregular acanthosis, hyperkeratosis, parakeratosis, and prominent chronic inflammation.
An indication that an individual is not working due to being laid off.
An indication that an individual is seeking work.

label.value: Raising Children Full-time or Keeping House

value.value: An indication that an individual is employed in their home, either raising children full-time or keeping house.
Transthyretin amyloid cardiomyopathy caused by mutation(s) in the TTR gene, encoding transthyretin.

Branch of applied psychology that emphasizes the study of machine design, the relationship between humans and machines, and the effects of machines on human behavior. Use a more specific term if possible. (PSY94)
